Managing to Learn, Learning to Manage: Harvard Business Review 70th
   Anniversary.  (HBR Sep-Oct 1992. p 133.)

Seventy years ago, in October 1922, the Harvard Business Review made its first
appearance.  The lead article was "Essential Groundwork for a Broad Executive
Theory" by then-HBS Dean Wallace B. Donham.  "The theory of business," he
wrote, "must develop to such a point that the executive, who will make the
necessary effort, may learn effectively from the experiences of others in the
past what to avoid and how to act under the conditions of the present.
Otherwise, business will continue unsystematic, haphazard, and for many men a
pathetic gamble.

For most of its history, business had been simple, individual, a family or
community affair.  In the expanding industrialization of the early 1900s,
business was finally recognized as a profession, and the theory base and
sharing of information mushroomed.  Over the years, HBR answered the need to
provide practical information and disseminate ideas.  Quality was the
overriding objective, continual improvement in managerial work was the mission.

A child of the twentieth century, the study of business administration mirrors
the history of our times.  To celebrate HBR's birthday and to learn from the
past, four illustrated gatefolds present the representative themes of each
decade.  Advertisements, photos, and colors of the times evoke each era, along
with excerpts from favorite HBR authors and articles.  Looking to the future,
recent quotes point to challenges for the century to come.

