The New Era of Eurocapitalism.  By Herbert A. Henzler.  (HBR Jul-Aug 1992. p
   57.)

Europe's capitalist system may be better suited to meet the demands of a global
economy than its American or Japanese counterparts.  In the years ahead, every
country must face the challenge of incorporating diverse groups under one roof
and improving the quality of life for all.  Here Europe's history gives its
managers a decided advantage.  Because their national markets are small,
European companies have long been internationally oriented. And unlike their
peers in the United States or Japan, European managers are accustomed to
working within the bounds of an implicit social contract.  A new generation of
"Europreneurs," such as Edzard Reuter of Daimler-Benz and Percy Barnevik of
ABB, has appeared to meet the challenges of the emerging global market.

