The Case of the Combative CFO.  By Nancy A. Nichols.  (HBR Jul-Aug 1992. p 14.)

The boardmembers of Minute Publishing must decide the fate of the company's
three-year-old national newspaper, America Today.  They can either follow the
advice of CEO Neil Harcum, who implores them to continue the paper's
publication, or CFO Peter Rawson, who wants to shut down the presses.  Both
sides have convincing arguments.  Harcum has a proven track record of making
newspapers profitable.  He argues that Minute "cannot allow the beancounters to
set policy." Rawson, on the other hand, explains that America Today is losing
$100 million a year and has broken Minute's 20-year string of earnings gains.
In making its decision, Minute's board will also be choosing a new CEO. Harcum
is retiring at the end of the year and doesn't want Rawson to take his place.

