The Case of the High-Risk Safety Product.  By W. Bruce Chew; Timothy B.
   Blodgett.  (HBR May-Jun 1992. p 14.)

After several days of meetings, J.F.  Winchester, president of MDC Industries,
felt no closer to deciding whether to buy a new and safer wallboard technology.
The product was being touted as revolutionary, but Winchester wondered, could
MDC afford to carry the flag

With almost the same flame-retardant qualities as other wall and ceiling
panels, Smoke-Safe had the advantage of giving off almost no fumes or smoke in
fire tests.  Most fire-related deaths, Winchester knew, are from smoke, not
flames.  Smoke-Safe also would cost about the same to manufacture as MDC's
current wallboard.

Still, Winchester hesitated.  MDC had several other good options for spending
the $5 million Smoke-Safe's inventor was asking; building plastics was only one
of its profit centers.  And the prospect of launching a campaign to change
building codes in order to market Smoke-Safe was financially and politically
daunting.  With only 18% of the wallboard market, MDC might not have the clout
to influence major cities to revise their codes.

Six experts in marketing, law, and ethics advise MDC Industries on how it can
balance ethical and business imperatives.

