Manufacturing's New Economies of Scale.  By Michael E. McGrath; Richard W.
   Hoole.  (HBR May-Jun 1992. p 94.)

Manufacturing companies now face the challenge of globally integrating their
operations.  Multinationals can no longer rely on sheer size and geographic
reach to dominate the volatile global arena.  But by integrating far-flung
plants into tightly connected, distributed production systems, companies can
seize the opportunity for a new manufacturing scale advantage

While there are no easy solutions to the need for change on such a large scale,
some manufacturers have created international teams for different functions;
others have emphasized doing a critical activity only once.  With a network of
flexible plants all over the world, manufacturers can achieve new economies of
scale and cut costs by eliminating redundant processes.  But in becoming
globally integrated, companies must also balance the tension between a central
authority and independent units.  And they must focus specific changes in
functions by articulating a vision shared by the entire organization.

